      <ref slug="ops-tax-compliance"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Legal Compliance Checklist - Stage-by-Stage Implementation</title>

    <summary>A stage-gated compliance tracker for online businesses: Day 1 (entity, EIN, bank account, core policies), Month 1 (website legal pages, data protection, payment processing, IP), Year 1 (tax compliance, employment/contractor law, marketing law, industry-specific, insurance), and Ongoing (policy update cycle, data management, audits, legal counsel). The checklist verifies presence and process - it does not verify that policy text is accurate or legally sufficient, which requires attorney review.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Most online-business legal failures come not from ignorance of what is required but from skipping the implementation step. A staged checklist forces the founder to work through obligations systematically by phase, rather than treating compliance as a one-time task. The ongoing cadence (quarterly policy review, regulatory monitoring) prevents the common failure of accurate-at-launch policies that drift from reality over time.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch: confirm all Day 1 items are in place before going live</item>
        <item>Post-launch (Month 1): complete data protection, payment, and IP items</item>
        <item>Quarterly audit: detect drift between policies and actual data flows/vendors</item>
        <item>After adding a new third-party integration (analytics, payments, AI provider)</item>
        <item>Producing compliance status snapshot for investor/acquirer due diligence</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Drafting policy text from scratch - use a generator (Termly, Iubenda) or counsel; this checklist verifies coverage, not wording</item>
        <item>Industry-regulated sectors (HIPAA, FINRA, FERPA, PCI-DSS) - baseline only; need vertical-specific checklists and legal review</item>
        <item>M&amp;A or fundraising legal due diligence - broader scope (cap table, IP chain, employment, contracts)</item>
        <item>Disputes, takedowns, demand letters - adversarial process, not checklist-driven</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="day-1-foundation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Complete all Day 1 items before accepting any payment or collecting any user data.</statement>
        <rationale>Legal and data-protection obligations attach at the moment of business activity, not at scale. Pre-revenue compliance is cheaper than retrofitted compliance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Business entity chosen and registered (LLC, S-Corp, C-Corp, or sole proprietor)</item>
        <item>EIN obtained or applied for</item>
        <item>Business bank account opened (separate from personal)</item>
        <item>Terms of Service drafted and published</item>
        <item>Privacy Policy drafted (GDPR/CCPA-aware) and published</item>
        <item>Cookie Policy created if website uses cookies</item>
        <item>Refund/Return Policy documented</item>
        <item>Business license obtained if required by state</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="month-1-post-launch">
      <list>
        <item>Terms of Service and Privacy Policy linked in website footer</item>
        <item>Contact information publicly accessible on site</item>
        <item>Consent mechanism implemented for personal data collection</item>
        <item>Marketing email opt-out mechanism working and tested</item>
        <item>GDPR compliance verified if serving EU customers (consent, DPO contact if required)</item>
        <item>CCPA compliance verified if serving California customers (Do Not Sell link if applicable)</item>
        <item>PCI-DSS compliance verified for payment processing</item>
        <item>Trademark search completed for business name and logo</item>
        <item>Licenses for any third-party content (images, fonts, code) confirmed</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="year-1-comprehensive">
      <list>
        <item>Tax professional (CPA/accountant) engaged</item>
        <item>Quarterly tax estimate process established</item>
        <item>Sales tax nexus determined by state</item>
        <item>Contractor agreements finalized and on file</item>
        <item>CAN-SPAM compliance verified for email marketing (physical address, unsubscribe)</item>
        <item>Industry-specific regulations identified and documented</item>
        <item>General liability insurance obtained</item>
        <item>Cyber liability insurance obtained if handling user data</item>
        <item>Trademark registration initiated for high-value brand assets</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ongoing-continuous">
      <rule>
        <statement>Establish a quarterly policy-review cycle. Assign a calendar reminder and treat it as a recurring sprint task, not an optional maintenance item.</statement>
        <rationale>Policies become inaccurate as the product evolves. A privacy policy written at launch that does not reflect current data flows is a compliance liability and erodes user trust.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Regulatory change monitoring (FTC, EDPB, ICO, state privacy laws, EU AI Act)</item>
        <item>Policies updated within 30 days of material regulatory change</item>
        <item>Data retention policy enforced and deletion procedure tested</item>
        <item>GDPR right-to-deletion process (DSAR) verified quarterly</item>
        <item>Data breach notification plan reviewed and contacts current</item>
        <item>Compliance documentation stored securely with version history</item>
        <item>Third-party vendor list reconciled against privacy policy disclosures</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="website-specific-requirements">
      <list>
        <item>SSL/HTTPS installed on all pages</item>
        <item>Cookie consent banner present and compliant (no pre-ticked boxes, equal-prominence reject button)</item>
        <item>WCAG 2.1 AA accessibility verified</item>
        <item>Data access/correction/deletion request process documented and accessible</item>
        <item>Privacy policies for all analytics and tracking tools verified</item>
        <item>CDN/hosting provider data practices reviewed</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="common-failure-patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>No LLC or entity formation - business operates as sole proprietor with no liability protection.</description>
        <reason>Personal assets are exposed to business liability. A single lawsuit or regulatory fine reaches the founder's personal bank account, home, and savings.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Copy-pasted privacy policy from a competitor or template that does not reflect actual data practices.</description>
        <reason>A policy that does not match reality is worse than no policy: it creates a documented false statement. Regulators (FTC, EDPB) treat this as a deceptive practice independent of whether harm occurred.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Policies updated silently without user notification on material changes.</description>
        <reason>Material changes to privacy terms require user notification under GDPR (Article 13/14), some state laws, and trust norms. Silent updates erode trust and may expose the business to regulatory action.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>GDPR compliance treated as a one-time checkbox at launch rather than an ongoing operational process.</description>
        <reason>GDPR applies to every new integration, new data flow, new market, and every change in data processors. Post-launch changes (adding an analytics tool, enabling AI features) reopen compliance obligations.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cookie consent banner uses pre-ticked boxes or makes "reject all" harder to find than "accept all".</description>
        <reason>EDPB guidelines explicitly prohibit dark patterns in consent interfaces. Non-compliant banners from major services have received multi-million euro fines. Consent must be freely given, specific, informed, and unambiguous.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No written contracts with contractors - work is commissioned verbally or via email without a signed agreement.</description>
        <reason>Without a contract, IP ownership is ambiguous (contractor may own the work they created), payment terms are disputed, and confidentiality is unprotected. A contractor agreement costs less than one hour of legal time to prepare from a template.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="audit-scope-and-agent-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>This checklist verifies presence and process, not legal sufficiency. "Privacy policy exists" is NOT the same as "privacy policy is accurate and legally compliant." Always distinguish between presence checks (automated) and content accuracy checks (require attorney review).</statement>
        <rationale>Agents frequently conflate "page exists" with "compliant." A privacy policy that says "we do not collect data" for a product that collects extensive data is worse than having no policy - it is an affirmative false statement.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not auto-publish any policy draft. All policy changes require: redline (diff vs prior version), human + counsel review gate, approval log entry, and then publication with effective-date update.</statement>
        <rationale>Policy edits that bypass counsel review and change log create litigation risk and hide changes from the legal record.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Audit cookie consent in both EU and non-EU locales. EU requires opt-in (pre-ticked boxes prohibited, reject must be as easy as accept). CCPA requires opt-out. Do not assume one pattern satisfies both.</statement>
        <rationale>Cookie scanners running against default (US) locale miss EU-specific requirements. Re-run audits with EU IP or locale headers to check the compliant path.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>When auditing cookie compliance, also run after user login. Many analytics trackers activate only for authenticated users and are missed by logged-out scans.</statement>
        <rationale>Authenticated-only trackers (e.g. session replay, product analytics with user IDs) are frequently the highest-risk data flows and the ones most often missed by standard cookie audits.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Data Subject Access Requests (right to access, correct, delete, export) must be routed to a human review queue. Never auto-respond to DSAR emails. Never auto-execute data deletion without identity verification.</statement>
        <rationale>Auto-responding to a deletion request without verifying identity could delete the wrong user's data. Identity verification requirements are specified in GDPR and CCPA and cannot be satisfied by email alone.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Run the checklist as an automated audit pass: agent fetches the live site, parses footer links, checks policy pages exist, scrapes the cookie banner, diffs declared vs actual third parties (cross-reference against script tags and network requests). Output structured findings with status per item. Pair with ops-legal-basics for context on each obligation, and ops-tax-compliance for entity/payment registrations. Human counsel reviews any flagged item before action.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-growth-agent (source README) owns the audit pass and report generation; faion-researcher for jurisdiction-specific obligations when expanding markets; security-review skill overlap on data-handling and vendor inventory; General-purpose Claude subagent with WebFetch pulls live policy pages and produces a diff against the canonical version stored in repo.</p>
      <p>Prompt pattern: Fetch url/privacy and url/terms. Parse and return: last-updated date, list of third parties named, list of user rights stated, presence/absence of: GDPR DPO contact, CCPA "Do Not Sell" link, CAN-SPAM physical address. Output as JSON aligned with the checklist.</p>
      <p>Second pattern: Given declared vendors=list and actual vendors detected from network log=list, output the gap (declared-not-used, used-not-declared) and rank by privacy impact.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-services">
      <p>CLI tools: lighthouse audits cookie + privacy basics; puppeteer / playwright headless render to capture cookies + 3rd-party requests; curl + jq pull and parse policy pages; pa11y accessibility (sometimes coupled with consent banner usability); cookiepedia-cli (community) identify third-party cookie origins; gh track policy versions in git, diff updates.</p>
      <p>Services: Termly (SaaS, partial) generator + monitor; no public API for solo tier. Manual export. Iubenda (SaaS, yes) API for policy generation, consent tracking, DPA inventory. OneTrust (SaaS, yes) Enterprise-tier API; overkill for solopreneur. Cookiebot / Usercentrics (SaaS, yes) API + JS SDK; generates cookie reports automatically. Osano (SaaS, yes) API + dashboard; good agent fit for DSAR workflows. Vanta / Drata / Secureframe (SaaS, yes) Compliance automation (SOC 2, ISO, GDPR) - API surfaces evidence, controls, vendor reviews. TrustArc (SaaS, partial) Enterprise; API limited. Stripe Atlas (SaaS, no) One-time formation; not an audit tool.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Version-control your policies in git; review every PR that changes /privacy or /terms. Treat them as code.</item>
        <item>Maintain a vendor-inventory file (CSV or JSON) that lists every third party receiving user data; update whenever a new SDK/script is added. The privacy policy must match this file.</item>
        <item>Re-audit on every: new feature launch, new vendor integration, new market entry, regulatory news event.</item>
        <item>Notify users by email on material privacy changes - silent updates erode trust and violate some jurisdictions' rules.</item>
        <item>Date-stamp every policy and keep an immutable changelog at the bottom of the page.</item>
        <item>For GDPR specifically: implement a working DSAR (data subject access request) endpoint and test it quarterly. The checkmark is meaningless if the workflow is broken.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Agents will mark "ToS exists" as compliant without reading content. Always require a content-extraction step that verifies key sections (limitation of liability, governing law, IP ownership, payment terms). LLM-drafted policies often hallucinate clauses or import US-specific terms into EU contexts. Treat all generated text as a draft for human counsel. Agents struggle to distinguish CCPA's "Do Not Sell or Share" from GDPR's "Object to Processing" - both must coexist for cross-border sites; check separately. Cookie scanners run against logged-out state by default and miss authenticated-only trackers. Re-run after login. Auto-generated DSAR responses risk leaking other users' data when joins are misconfigured. Mandatory human review before sending. Compliance is a moving target - don't pin the agent to a static checklist; re-derive obligations on each major regulatory update (state privacy laws in US ship monthly). Privilege concerns: legal-counsel work product fed to LLMs may lose attorney-client privilege. Don't pipe lawyer drafts through external LLM APIs without review.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/policy-update-notification.md" purpose="User notification email template for material policy changes."/>
    </templates>

